  "location": "On the phone, anywhere in HK",
  "context": "Most HK restaurants take phone bookings, especially for groups of four or more. You'll need to give your name, party size, time, and sometimes a phone number. Polite phone Cantonese is slightly more formal than face-to-face.",
  "cultural_note": "In Hong Kong, the person who booked the table is understood to be hosting, which means they pay. Attempting to pay the bill when you're a guest triggers the ritual of 搶埋單 (coeng2 maai4 daan1): a competitive scramble to grab the bill folder first. It reads as generosity, not aggression.",
